      "content": "Since you need a fast solution that handles huge queries on a sparse grid within 1.0s, the most robust approach is to use coordinate compression on the non-zero points to map them into a small Fenwick Tree (Binary Indexed Tree). First, collect all unique x and y coordinates from the sparse input, sort them, and compress them into ranks (1 to K). This reduces the grid size to at most `min(num_points, 50000)` in each dimension, fitting easily in memory. Then, build the Fenwick tree by processing points and calculating prefix sums in O(log K) time per point. For each query, use the compressed coordinates to perform a standard range sum query in O(log K) time. This avoids the massive memory allocation of a full matrix while keeping the query overhead low enough to pass the strict time limit.\n\nHere is the optimized Python solution using `sys.stdin` for speed and a 1D Fenwick Tree on compressed coordinates:\n\n```python\nimport sys\n\ndef solve():\n    input = sys.stdin.read\n    data = input().split()\n    iterator = iter(data)\n    \n    N = int(next(iterator))\n    M = int(next(iterator))",
